<paper id="1554045856"><title>Deciding Finiteness of Petri Nets Up To Bisimulation</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="University of Ostrava" id="8200839">Petr Jancar</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2123449190">Javier Esparza</author></authors><n_citation>35</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>58289885</reference><reference>1529624861</reference><reference>1598641851</reference><reference>1964087553</reference><reference>1965551437</reference><reference>2005312844</reference><reference>2008435081</reference><reference>2106557750</reference><reference>2161597229</reference><reference>2394903686</reference></references><venue id="1141821850" type="C">International Colloquium on Automata, Languages and Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-61440-0_152</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.49931">Transition system</keyword><keyword weight="0.43051">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.42419">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.58951">Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.38518">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.652">Stochastic Petri net</keyword><keyword weight="0.52544">Decidability</keyword><keyword weight="0.66647">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Bisimulation equivalence</keyword><keyword weight="0.47767">Undecidable problem</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We study the following problems for strong and weak bisimulation equivalence: given a labelled Petri net and a finite transition system, are they equivalent?; given a labelled Petri net, is it equivalent to some (unspecified) finite transition system? We show that both problems are decidable for strong bisimulation and undecidable for weak bisimulation.</abstract></paper>